deploys the show-and-tell modality of a museum to engage with the inner life of heat, rain, stone, and swamp, no less than with the life of gold and cocaine. This effort to find a poetry of words becoming things is brought to a head by the explosive qualities of those sublime fetishes of evil beauty, gold and cocaine. At its core, Taussig's museum is about the lure of forbidden things, charged substances that transgress moral codes, the distinctions we use to make sense of the world, and above all the conventional way we write stories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCocaine industry -- Colombia -- Santa María (Cauca). 0aCocaine industryzColombiazSanta María (Cauca). 0aDrug traffic -- Colombia -- Santa María (Cauca). 0aDrug trafficzColombiazSanta María (Cauca). 0aGold mines and mining -- Colombia -- Santa María (Cauca). 0aGold mines and miningzColombiazSanta María (Cauca). 0aIndians of South America -- Colombia -- Santa María (Cauca) -- Economic conditions. 0aIndians of South America -- Colombia -- Santa María (Cauca) -- Social conditions. 0aIndians of South AmericazColombiazSanta María (Cauca)xEconomic conditions. 0aIndians of South AmericazColombiazSanta María (Cauca)xSocial conditions. 0aIndians, Treatment of -- Colombia -- Santa María (Cauca). 0aIndians, Treatment ofzColombiazSanta María (Cauca). 0aSlavery -- Colombia -- Santa María (Cauca) -- History. 0aSlaveryzColombiazSanta María (Cauca)xHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agold museum, pacific coast, colombia, miners, cocaine, rain forest, slavery, slaves, labor, colonialism, transgression, forbidden, afro-colombian, banco de la republica, race, racism, exploitation, capitalism, wealth, politics, history, fetish, corruption, indigenous, native, santa maraia, cauca, mines, drug traffic, nonfiction.